ly 1501":"14 July 1501","1528":"1528","1439":"1439","about 1460":"about 1460","1537":"1537","Lenham, Kent, England":"Lenham, Kent, England","Wolvedon, England":"England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Attwaters","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Middle English  <i>at (the) water</i> ‘(dweller) beside the water’ (Old English  <i>wæter</i>), usually a reference to a pond, stream, or river.  Compare  Bywater   and   Waterer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bywater","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone living by a lake or river, from Middle English <i>by</i> ‘by, beside’ + <i>water</i> ‘water’.","Irish: pseudo-translation (due to confusion with <i>sruth</i> ‘stream’) of Gaelic <b>Ó Srutháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sruithán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>sruith</i> ‘sage, elder’. <i>Bywater</i> is found as the English form of this Gaelic name in County Cork, while in Mayo the usual Anglicization is   Ryan  ."]},{"name":"Waterer","meanings":["English: locative name from Middle English * <i>waterer</i>, denoting one who lived by a stretch of water such as a village pond or a stream, as proven by the 1547–50 alias  <i>Atwater</i>. Topographic names in  <i>-er</i> were especially common in Surrey, Sussex, and Hants. This example became particularly numerous as a hereditary surname in Surrey, where it was still most frequent in the 1881 Census. There is no evidence to support Reaney’s view that the name was occupational, from Middle English  <i>waterer</i> ‘a person responsible for watering animals’ (attested once before 1500 in   MED  ), or Cottle’s view that it meant ‘water-seller’."]},{"name":"Atwater","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone whose dwelling was by a river or lake, Middle English <i>atte water</i> ‘at the water’.","History: This surname was established from an early date in New England. David Atwater was one of the group of settlers who founded the New Haven colony in 1638."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":16,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir John Attwaters Wolvedon was born in 1439, in Lenham, Kent, England as the son of Richard Wolvedon. He had at least 2 sons and 3 daughters with Mary Ann Attwaters. He died on 14 July 1501, in his hometown, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1439–14 July 1501":"1439–14. juuli 1501","1439–1501":"1439–1501","1439–1558":"1439–1558","1458–Female":"1458–Surnud","1460–Female":"1460–Surnud","1466–1528":"1466–1528","1468–1514":"1468–1514","1469–1537":"1469–1537","1440–1500":"1440–1500","1440":"1440","ABT 1468":"umbes 1468","1460":"1460","1514":"1514","1558":"1558","1469":"1469","1458":"1458","1468":"1468","1501":"1501","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","about 1458":"umbes 1458","about 1466":"umbes 1466","14 July 1501":"14. juuli 1501","1528":"1528","1439":"1439","about 1460":"umbes 1460","1537":"1537","Lenham, Kent, England":"Lenham, Kent, 